<br>
The bible is basically a very long collection of fables.  Aesop used animals and the bible uses parables, but they teach the same thing.  If you don't want people to rape, but you can't convince them with rational thought that there's no reason to in a time when women are considered property, you convince them that committing this act will send them to an eternity of fire and brimstone and endless torture.  You tell them, I could care less if you do it, but this supreme being will fry your ass for all eternity.  When that works, you write it down.  You move on to people who are sick or dying because they live in filth, convince them the big woohoo in the sky doesn't like it and maybe time that revelation with a good electrical storm to prove your point.  They start bathing once a week, it works write it down.  So the story grew.  Along the way they tweaked things.  After a while they decided that sacrificing goats on a regular basis was neither sanitary nor food concious, so they let that one go.  The bit about if your son is lazy and won't work, drag him into the street and stone him to death for all the neighbors to see - that must have got a bit messy after a while because they let that one go too.<br>
<br>
Then they had to fix up the holidays.  They had thousands of people to convert, but it wasn't working out because the so-called pagan holidays (meaning anything non-christian) were more fun.  So, they decided well yeah we know jesus was really born on this day, but those pagans have this big party in December, so lets say he was born December 25th.  We know when he died, but damn, those pagans have another big blast in April taking all our mealtickets, err followers, away, so we'll say he died in the middle of their festival.  We'll move new years to just after Christmas to throw off the timing on all their other events, and eventually we'll have the only reliable schedule around.<br>
<br>
The bible sitting on your nightstand today is a far cry from the original.  I would seriously doubt that anyone, even the vatican in all its supposed wisdom and glory, can trace back to the original parts.  The odds of all that papyrus surviving long enough to be discovered and preserved are just too heavily stacked in favor of decomposition.<br>
<br>
Faith is a mind induced drug.  It alters your perceptions just like alcohol or marijuana will, just in different extremes.  It can be beneficial in moderation, and it can be destructive when it is given total control. <p><img src=http://www.kaseyspace.com/EQ/nenasig5.jpg align=center>
